Customer Segmentation Analysis¶

Q1. What is Customer Segmentation and why is it important from marketing perspective?¶

Answer 1:¶

Customer segmentation is a way of grouping or clustering clients based on shared demographic, psychographic and behavioural features such as age, gender, interests and spending habits. Occupation, gender, age, location, and marital status are all different examples of demographic traits. Social class, lifestyle, and personality traits are all psychographic features. Spending habits, consuming patterns, product/service usage, and previously acquired products are all behavioural traits.

The power of customer segmentation, could benefit in following ways:

  1. Improved marketing campaigns: customer segmentation makes it possible to build tailored marketing messages to each particular segment. In fact, segmented campaigns have almost a 15% higher open rate than non-segmented ones.
  2. Better offerings: knowing our customers allows to develop an offer for them so that it meets their particular needs to the best extent.
  3. Greater return on sales: adjusting marketing efforts to companys most successful customer segments can bring about an increase in revenue in the long run.
  4. Increased loyalty and retention: personalization in every case matters. 80% of clients are more likely to do business with a brand that provides personalized experiences. So, customized content and individualized approach are what savours customer satisfaction and retention.
  5. Untapped cross-selling and upselling opportunities: by segmenting existing and potential clients into groups, we realize what things they could be more interested in. It promotes the update of new products and services relevant to the targeted audience.

Conclusively, it is important because it aids in the identification of the most likely clients, makes it easier to manage and communicate with a specific audience. It boosts customer satisfaction, loyalty, and retention by improving customer relationships through better comprehending segment demands. Allows upselling and cross-selling opportunities by creating special offers for certain clients in order to persuade them to purchase more items. Customer segmentation aids in the identification of new customers by allowing for a better knowledge of the demands of various categories. Each customer is valuable, and segmentation helps to create value for each one.

Perform RFM Analysis¶

  • For Recency, Calculate the number of days between present date and date of last purchase for each customer.
  • For Frequency, Calculate the number of orders for each customer.
  • For Monetary, Calculate sum of purchase price for each customer

Q6. What is wrong with this table think ??¶

Answer 6¶

In the table, for customer ID 12748, it shows monetary value as '0' and respective frequency is 4596 which is realistically impossible. The column have been mislabelled in the above table. While the column InvoiceDate must be recency it has been mislabelled as monetary. TotalPrice must be monetary but has been mislabelled as recency.Apparently, Total Price should be monetary and the days difference from present should be recency, hence the column headers need relabelling. Also the difference between certain dates is not correct hence number of the days are incorrect , further each transaction has been counted as a frequency whereas one order should be counted as a frequency.

Q7. What does this above chart tell ?¶

Answer 7:¶

The above graph shows the distribution of recency data for United Kingdom with the most recent puchases reoccurring within 0-50 days, there is around 100 transactions that range after 100 to 370 days.

  • The above graph shows that consumers who purchased within the last two months (up to 50 days) are more numerous, and we also have some lost customers (customers who have not returned in over a year are referred to as "lost customers.")
  • Customers who had just visited would make more revenue than those who had visited in the past.
  • Our attention should be on the most recent consumers rather than those who visited a long time ago, because the most current customers will provide the majority of recent sales.

The above graph shows the distribution of recency data for United Kingdom with the most puchases were made 7-12 months (250 - 370 days) ago, there is around 170 transactions that ocurred within 20-90 days and puchases were lower 100 to 190 days ago. Not many purchases are being made recently, most of our data is showing records that are 4 months old.

def r_score(x):
    if x <= quintiles['recency'][.2]:
        return 5
    elif x <= quintiles['recency'][.4]:
        return 4
    elif x <= quintiles['recency'][.6]:
        return 3
    elif x <= quintiles['recency'][.8]:
        return 2
    else:
        return 1
    
def fm_score(x, c):
    if x <= quintiles[c][.2]:
        return 1
    elif x <= quintiles[c][.4]:
        return 2
    elif x <= quintiles[c][.6]:
        return 3
    elif x <= quintiles[c][.8]:
        return 4
    else:
        return 5

Q10. Comment on the above chart¶

Answer 10¶

  • The graph is showing data the distributed in six segments of customers.
  • Graph is suggesting that we have 37% customers at churn risk (low RFM) and only 2% customers are permanent customers whom we wouldn't loose (low recency but high frequency & monetary)
  • 25% are the frequent buying champions (high RFM) and 18% are loyal customers.(moderate RFM)
  • We should create value for our new 3% customers (high recency and low frequency /monetary) and divert our attention to promote, gather feedback from other 12% who need attention.
  • The stronger segments are colored in green. Champions are adaptive and can be developed to be loyal. Loyal customers should be rewarded.

Q 20. What is the purpose of the above code¶

Answer 20¶

In order to compare data the above code calculated z score to normalize the data, rfm_clean dataset contains all the values with z score less than 3. The values more than 3 z score are three standard deviations away from central tendency and are unlikely to represent the data. The purpose is to eliminate z values that are beyond the threshold limit. The potential outliers will be eliminated as we shoud not consider them in analysis.

# Choose number of Clusters using the elbow method
# Within cluster sum of squares (wcss)
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
# start with 10 number of clusters
wcss = []
for i in range(1,10):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters =i, init = 'k-means++', max_iter =300, n_init =10, random_state =0)
    kmeans.fit(X)
    wcss.append(kmeans.inertia_)
plt.plot(range(1,10), wcss)
plt.title('The Elbow Method')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('WCSS')
plt.show()

Q 24. Comment on the plots¶

We have three clusters 0,1,2. We see the distribution of these clusters within a combination of two variables.

Frequency vs. Monetary: Positive relationship between frequency and monetary. As frequency increases the monetary increases. Although the relationship is wide. The clusters are layered. Cluster 0 is at lower layer, the blue cluster has low frequency as well as low monetary value (range: frequency(0-400), monetary(0-1800), these customers are not frequenct customers, must be buying odd products and spend less. Cluster 2, is the next up , the green cluster, these customers are spending more and only a handful among them have more frequency. They are spending in the range of 1800-4100, they have similar frequency to blue cluster however around 1% of these have frequency upto 750. Cluster 1, the orange cluster has the highest monetary distribution. Their spending ranges from 4200-10000. There frequency matches that of other two clusters, however again nearly 1% of these have ver high frequency.

Recency vs. Monetary

Negative relationship between Recency and monetary. As recency increases the monetary decreases. That implies that most of the purchases are from recent orders. There are some orders that were placed nearly a year ago. The clusters are layered. Cluster 0 is at lower layer, the blue cluster has high recency, orders are old, and have low monetary value (range: recency(0-400), monetary(0-1800), these orders were old, only 30% of recent orders have a monetary value between (0-1800). Green cluster is the customers that have purchased within last six months, they have spnd moderately between 1800 - 4200. Orange cluster, with maximum spending are customers who have spend recently within less than 50 days. Only very few purchases are out of this distribution and were older purchases.

Recency vs. frequency

The graph is no longer layered and all the clusters seem to overlap each other. Graph is highly concentrated towards 0-100 recency and 0-400 frequency distribution.

Evaluate Clustering¶

In [135]:
# Import libraries
from sklearn import cluster
from sklearn import metrics
In [136]:
# Calculate Silhouette score for different cluster values
krange = list(range(2,5))
avg_silhouettes = []
for n in krange:
    model = cluster.KMeans(n_clusters=n, random_state=10)
    cluster_assignments = model.fit_predict(X1)

    silhouette_avg = metrics.silhouette_score(X1, cluster_assignments)
    avg_silhouettes.append(silhouette_avg)
    
    # PLot the score
plt.plot(krange, avg_silhouettes)
plt.xlabel("$K$")
plt.ylabel("Average Silhouette Score")
plt.show()
In [137]:
# Calculate Silhouette score for different cluster values
krange = list(range(2,10))
avg_silhouettes = []
for n in krange:
    model = cluster.KMeans(n_clusters=n, random_state=10)
    cluster_assignments = model.fit_predict(X1)

    silhouette_avg = metrics.silhouette_score(X1, cluster_assignments)
    avg_silhouettes.append(silhouette_avg)
    
    # PLot the score
plt.plot(krange, avg_silhouettes)
plt.xlabel("$K$")
plt.ylabel("Average Silhouette Score")
plt.show()

According to Silhouette principle, we are trying to assess if data points have been appropriately mapped to their own clusters when compared to the other clusters. Also we try to establish that which is the optimum cluster size, as the size of the clusters are increasing Silhouette score is decreasing that means data points are not being mapped to their own clusters properly. Having few clusters like K=2, would split the data in only two parts resulting in not much clarification or information gain. Having 4 clusters will give more information but it might not be true as compared with its pairs. In a nut shell, K=3 is perhaps the best cluster size given the data and is providing best insights.
